  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law in the United States, money laundering is a serious offense with severe penalties. The specific penalties can vary depending on the nature and severity of the crime, but generally, they include the following:\n\n1. **Imprisonment**: Individuals convicted of money laundering can face substantial prison sentences. For example:\n   - Under **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956** (which covers financial transactions involving the proceeds of unlawful activity), the maximum penalty is **up to 20 years in prison**.\n   - Under **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957** (which involves engaging in monetary transactions with criminally derived property of more than $10,000), the maximum penalty is **up to 10 years in prison**.\n\n2. **Fines**: Convictions for money laundering can also result in significant financial penalties. These fines can be substantial, often reaching **up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction**, whichever is greater.\n\n3. **Civil Penalties**: In addition to criminal penalties, individuals and entities may face civil penalties, including forfeiture of assets involved in or derived from the money laundering activity.\n\n4. **Forfeiture of Assets**: The government can seize and forfeit property, funds, or other assets connected to the money laundering scheme. This includes any financial gains or assets purchased with laundered funds.\n\n5. **Enhanced Penalties for Aggravating Factors**: Penalties can be more severe if certain aggravating factors are present, such as:\n   - Involvement in organized crime or terrorism financing.\n   - Large-scale or repeated offenses.\n   - Laundering funds derived from particularly serious crimes (e.g., drug trafficking, human trafficking, or fraud).\n\n6. **Collateral Consequences**: Beyond legal penalties, individuals convicted of money laundering may face additional consequences, such as:\n   - Loss of professional licenses.\n   - Difficulty obtaining future employment.\n   - Damage to personal and professional reputation.\n\nThese penalties highlight the federal government's commitment to combating money laundering and related financial crimes. If you or someone you know is facing such charges, it is crucial to seek legal counsel from an experienced attorney.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
